---
import Atlas from '@/layouts/Atlas.astro';
import { getInventory, getPackage, getFlow, getState } from '@/lib/atlas';

const inv = await getInventory();
const ch = inv.chapters.find(c => c.id === '03')!;
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');

const sdkCore = await getPackage('sdk-core');
const webSdk  = await getPackage('web-sdk');
const nodeSdk = await getPackage('node-sdk');
const sdkRs   = await getPackage('sdk-rs');

const flow  = await getFlow('siwe-login');
const state = await getState('session');

const pkgHref = (id: string) => `${base}/pkg/${id.replace(/\//g, '--')}/`;

// Lanes for the sequence diagram in display order.
const lanes = ['App', 'Web', 'Auth', 'Wallet', 'Wasm', 'Node'];

// Layout constants for the SVG sequence diagram.
const laneW = 130;
const padX = 24;
const stepH = 30;
const headerH = 44;
const seqW = padX * 2 + laneW * lanes.length;
const seqH = headerH + stepH * (flow.steps.length + 1);
---
<Atlas chapter="03" title={ch.title} crumb={`03 · ${ch.title}`}>
  <article class="prose" style="padding: 56px 64px; max-width: 1100px;">
    <div class="label">chapter 03 · {ch.read} · voice: {ch.voice}</div>
    <h1 style="margin-top: 14px;">SIWE → <span class="squig">session</span></h1>
    <p>
      Sign-In with Ethereum is the front door. From the consumer's seat it
      looks like one call: <code>tinycloud.signIn()</code>. From the inside
      it's a six-actor dance — the app, the SDK shell, the auth handler, the
      user's wallet, the WASM kernel, and the TinyCloud node. By the end of
      this chapter you'll know what each step actually does, and where the
      session that comes out the other side is stored.
    </p>

    <h2>one call, six actors</h2>

    <div class="mermaid-wrap" style={`margin: 22px 0; min-height: ${seqH + 30}px; position: relative; padding: 18px 12px 12px;`}>
      <span class="cap">flow/siwe-login.json</span>

      <svg width={seqW} height={seqH} style="display: block; margin: 0 auto;">
        <defs>
          <marker id="ah-03" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="9" refY="5" markerWidth="7" markerHeight="7" orient="auto">
            <path d="M0,0 L10,5 L0,10 z" fill="var(--accent)" />
          </marker>
          <marker id="ah-03-ret" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="9" refY="5" markerWidth="7" markerHeight="7" orient="auto">
            <path d="M0,0 L10,5 L0,10 z" fill="var(--ink-3)" />
          </marker>
        </defs>

        {/* Lane headers + lifelines */}
        {lanes.map((name, i) => {
          const x = padX + laneW * i + laneW / 2;
          return (
            <g>
              <rect x={padX + laneW * i + 8} y={8} width={laneW - 16} height={28}
                    rx={4} fill="var(--accent)" stroke="var(--accent)" />
              <text x={x} y={26} text-anchor="middle"
                    font-family="JetBrains Mono, monospace" font-size="12"
                    font-weight="600" fill="var(--paper)">{name}</text>
              <line x1={x} y1={headerH} x2={x} y2={seqH - 8}
                    stroke="var(--ink-4)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3 3" />
            </g>
          );
        })}

        {/* Steps */}
        {flow.steps.map((s: any, i: number) => {
          const fromI = lanes.indexOf(s.from);
          const toI = lanes.indexOf(s.to);
          if (fromI < 0 || toI < 0) return null;
          const y = headerH + stepH * (i + 1);
          const x1 = padX + laneW * fromI + laneW / 2;
          const x2 = padX + laneW * toI + laneW / 2;
          const isRet = !!s.ret;
          const stroke = isRet ? 'var(--ink-3)' : 'var(--accent)';
          const dash = isRet ? '4 4' : 'none';
          const marker = isRet ? 'url(#ah-03-ret)' : 'url(#ah-03)';
          const labelX = (x1 + x2) / 2;
          return (
            <g>
              <line x1={x1} y1={y} x2={x2} y2={y}
                    stroke={stroke} stroke-width="1.4"
                    stroke-dasharray={dash} marker-end={marker} />
              <text x={labelX} y={y - 5} text-anchor="middle"
                    font-family="JetBrains Mono, monospace" font-size="11"
                    fill="var(--ink)">{s.msg}</text>
            </g>
          );
        })}
      </svg>
    </div>

    <h2>step by step, what each actor does</h2>

    <h3>1 · the wallet handshake</h3>
    <p>
      The first thing <code>WebUserAuthorization.signIn()</code> does is
      reach for a wallet — typically <code>window.ethereum</code> — and
      request connection. The wallet returns an address and a chain ID, both
      of which become permanent parts of the session identity. On Node, a
      <code>PrivateKeySigner</code> takes the wallet's place and the address
      is computed from the key locally; there's no popup.
    </p>

    <h3>2 · the session key</h3>
    <p>
      Before the user signs anything, the auth handler asks WASM for a fresh
      Ed25519 keypair via <code>createSessionManager().createSessionKey(id)</code>.
      That keypair lives entirely inside the WASM heap — JS only ever sees its
      JWK and DID. It's the key that will sign every <em>subsequent</em>
      capability invocation, so the wallet only has to sign once.
    </p>

    <h3>3 · prepare the SIWE</h3>
    <p>
      With the session DID in hand,
      <code>prepareSession({'{abilities, address, chainId, domain, jwk, …}'})</code>
      crosses the seam into Rust. WASM builds a SIWE message whose ReCap
      resource encodes the abilities map — a nested record of
      <code>{'service → path → action[]'}</code> the session is allowed to
      invoke. The same call returns the SIWE string, the session metadata,
      and a placeholder for the eventual signature.
    </p>

    <h3>4 · sign and complete</h3>
    <p>
      The wallet (or signer) signs <code>prepared.siwe</code> exactly as
      returned — no re-construction, no canonicalization. The signature
      flows back into <code>completeSessionSetup({'{...prepared, signature}'})</code>,
      which produces a delegation: a UCAN whose subject is the session DID
      and whose root authority is the wallet's signature over the SIWE+ReCap.
      This is the artifact the node will accept.
    </p>

    <h3>5 · server roundtrip</h3>
    <p>
      The browser surface posts to <code>/tcw-login</code> on the configured
      TinyCloud host with the delegation header. The node verifies the SIWE
      against the wallet address, walks the ReCap, checks the nonce against
      its replay store, and binds a session token to the delegation. From
      Node code the equivalent step is <code>activateSessionWithHost(host, delegationHeader)</code>
      — same protocol, no HTTP cookie indirection.
    </p>

    <h3>6 · persist + restore</h3>
    <p>
      What lands in storage isn't the wallet's signature alone — it's the
      <code>TinyCloudSession</code> bundle: address, chainId, sessionKey JWK,
      delegationCid, delegationHeader, the SIWE string, the signature, and
      the resolved spaceId. <code>BrowserSessionStorage</code> writes this to
      <code>localStorage</code> by default; <code>FileSessionStorage</code> in
      <a class="pkg-link" href={pkgHref(nodeSdk.id)}>{nodeSdk.npm}</a> writes
      to disk. On next boot the SDK rehydrates a <code>DelegatedAccess</code>
      (or its web equivalent) without prompting the wallet again.
    </p>

    <h2>where the state lives</h2>

    <div class="card" style="padding: 18px 22px; margin: 18px 0;">
      <div class="label" style="margin-bottom: 10px;">state/session.json — the FSM</div>
      <div class="row gap-12 wrap" style="margin-bottom: 14px;">
        {state.states.map((s: string) => (
          <span class="pill kind-sdk" style="font-size: 12px;">{s}</span>
        ))}
      </div>
      <div class="col gap-4" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 12px; color: var(--ink-2);">
        {state.transitions.map((t: string[]) => (
          <div>
            <span style="color: var(--ink);">{t[0]}</span>
            <span style="color: var(--ink-3); padding: 0 6px;">→</span>
            <span style="color: var(--ink);">{t[1]}</span>
            <span style="color: var(--accent); padding-left: 12px;">{t[2]}</span>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      The same FSM applies to both surfaces — only the inputs differ.
      <code>signOut()</code> wipes the session bundle and clears the
      <code>tinycloudModule</code> global on web; on Node it just empties
      the in-memory authorization. Expiry returns the FSM to
      <code>connected</code>, where a new <code>signIn()</code> rotates the
      session key and starts a fresh delegation chain — the wallet does not
      need to be prompted again so long as the previous SIWE is still valid.
    </p>

    <h2>delegated access — the restorable form</h2>
    <p>
      <a class="pkg-link" href={pkgHref(nodeSdk.id)}>{nodeSdk.npm}</a> exports
      <code>DelegatedAccess</code> as the canonical session shape. It holds
      everything required to invoke capabilities — the session JWK, the
      delegation header, the spaceId, the host — and nothing else. The
      browser side calls it <code>ClientSession</code>, but the bytes are the
      same. Either can be serialized, ferried across processes, and rehydrated
      against the kernel without ever bringing the wallet back into scope.
    </p>

    <h3>data this chapter reads</h3>
    <ul class="col gap-4">
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/inventory.json</li>
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/flow/siwe-login.json</li>
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/state/session.json</li>
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/pkg/sdk-core.json</li>
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/pkg/web-sdk.json</li>
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/pkg/node-sdk.json</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>where to read next</h3>
    <p>
      Chapter <a class="pkg-link" href={`${base}/04/`}>04</a> picks up the
      <code>spaceId</code> the session resolves and explains what a space
      <em>is</em> — the per-DID owner, the URI shape, and the KV API that
      hangs off it.
    </p>
  </article>
</Atlas>
